sui construct the fine moduli space of polarized logarithmic Hodge structures with additional structures. Even for a Hermitian symmetric domain D, the present theory is a refinement of the toroidal compactifications by Mumford et al. For general D, fine moduli spaces may have slits caused by Griffiths transversality at the boundary and be no longer locally compact. Second, Kato and Usui construct eight enlargements of D and describe their relations by a fundamental diagram, where four of these enlargements live in the Hodge theoretic area and the other four live in the algebra-group theoretic area. These two areas are connected by a continuous map given by the SL(2)-orbit theorem of Cattani-Kaplan-Schmid. This diagram is used for the construction in the first topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aHodge theory. 0aLogarithms. 0aMATHEMATICSvAlgebravLinear. 7aMATHEMATICS / Algebra / Linear.2bisacsh  aAlgebraic group.  aAlgebraic variety.  aAnalytic manifold.  aAnalytic space.  aAnnulus (mathematics).  aArithmetic group.  aAtlas (topology).  aCanonical map.  aClassifying space.  aCoefficient.  aCohomology.  aCompactification (mathematics).  aComplex manifold.  aComplex number.  aCongruence subgroup.  aConjecture.  aConnected component (graph theory).  aContinuous function.  aConvex cone.  aDegeneracy (mathematics).  aDiagram (category theory).  aDifferential form.  aDirect image functor.  aDivisor.  aElliptic curve.  aEquivalence class.  aExistential quantification.  aFinite set.  aFunctor.  aGeometry.  aHodge structure.  aHodge theory.  aHomeomorphism.  aHomomorphism.  aInverse function.  aIwasawa decomposition.  aLocal homeomorphism.  aLocal ring.  aLocal system.  aLogarithmic.  aMaximal compact subgroup.  aModular curve.  aModu